{"type":"message","id":"3e470520","parentId":"8dfc8465","timestamp":"2026-04-14T12:10:36.876Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me compare current sessions against heartbeat state:\n\n**Current session statuses (from sessions_list):**\n1. `agent:master-orchestrator:cron:ed2d0b5d-fc56-42eb-a8fc-973a48024df7` — running, updatedAt: 1776168607100 (12:10 UTC)\n2. `agent:master-orchestrator:cron:6f3323ef-607e-42a0-b946-611913081d31` — running, updatedAt: 1776168491925 (12:08 UTC)\n3. `agent:master-orchestrator:telegram:group:-5163901258` — running, updatedAt: 1776168426498 (12:07 UTC)\n\n\n4. `agent:master-orchestrator:cron:b653a6c0-143b-4b53-a242-034bc5fd9fca` — running, updatedAt: 1776167853466 (12:04 UTC)\n5. `agent:master-orchestrator:telegram:direct:6053576134` — done, endedAt: 1776162158012\n6. `agent:master-orchestrator:cron:e7885813-0446-4101-a171-941c2416848e` — running, updatedAt: 1776167170108 (11:59 UTC)\n7. `agent:master-orchestrator:main` — done\n\nLooking at the session list, most of the cron jobs are still running, though `cron:e7885813` shows a slightly older timestamp around 11:59 UTC. The main session and the Telegram direct session have completed.\n\n8. `agent:master-orchestrator:cron:ac986a8d-2425-40c7-835b-ed9b101b0bff` — running, updatedAt: 1776156272410 (10:30 UTC)\n\nI'm noticing a discrepancy between the heartbeat state and the current session list. The heartbeat reported this cron as stale, but it's still appearing in the sessions list. The timestamps don't quite align either—the heartbeat update from 12:04 UTC shows a later timestamp than the session's actual updatedAt time of 10:30 UTC, which suggests the heartbeat might be newer than what I'm seeing in the sessions data. I'm noticing a discrepancy in the timestamps—cron:ed2d0b5d shows updatedAt: 12:04 in the heartbeat state but 12:10 in the sessions list, which suggests either the heartbeat was captured mid-execution or there's something else going on with how these timestamps are being recorded.\n\nLooking at the heartbeat history, the last report was sent at 12:04 UTC, so the current time of 12:09 UTC is only about 5 minutes later, which falls within the normal reporting interval.\n\nComparing the session statuses to the heartbeat state, everything appears consistent — the main session ended around 11:59, and the cron jobs that were running in the heartbeat are still running now. No significant changes detected. I'm realizing the discrepancy: the heartbeat state captured `cron:ed2d0b5d` at 12:04 UTC with no message history, but by 12:08 UTC when the DTLX cron ran, that same session had grown to 5 messages—which means the cron session itself is actively running and accumulating messages between heartbeat captures. The timestamps suggest the cron job is executing across multiple checks, updating the session each time it fires. I'm comparing the current session state against the heartbeat data from 12:04 UTC, and everything checks out—the key sessions are still running as expected, so there's no meaningful change to report.\n\nLooking at the main orchestrator session more closely, it ended at 11:59 UTC according to the heartbeat record, but the sessions list shows 12:12 UTC, which is actually in the future from my current perspective. The heartbeat might be capturing stale data that's already shifted, so I shouldn't rely on it for real-time accuracy.\n\nThe critical sessions I need to track are the cron jobs that are actively running—those are the ones that could indicate system changes or issues.\n\nLooking at the data across all timestamps, the system appears stable with no new failures, blocked tasks, or session changes. Since there's nothing new to report, I should stay quiet and update the heartbeat timestamp in the state file to the current time.","thinkingSignature":"6e9683aeb879797e23ab2a78047c70fb664319254260bd118e838227557514c2"},{"type":"text","text":"Comparing current sessions against heartbeat state